<paragraph id="BF04A850FF8F8A158B0AFF1493A0FCD8" blockId="4.[279,1112,232,846]" pageId="4" pageNumber="372">
<emphasis id="8DCF7442FF8F8A158B0AFF14901FFF6B" bold="true" box="[306,624,232,253]" pageId="4" pageNumber="372">Biogeographical Comments.</emphasis>
The presence of this species in 
<collectingCountry id="C7ACE8C0FF8F8A1589E8FF14964FFF6B" box="[976,1056,232,253]" name="Mexico" pageId="4" pageNumber="372">México</collectingCountry>
considerably extends the distribution of the Tribe 
<taxonomicName id="78BBD3D3FF8F8A15893CFEFF9102FE8E" authorityName="Aurivillius" authorityYear="1912" box="[772,877,259,280]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="372" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Erlandiini">Erlandiini</taxonomicName>
in the Western Hemisphere and raises interesting biogeographical questions. The three species have been recorded only in the dry tropical communities, 
<taxonomicName id="78BBD3D3FF8F8A15896CFEC591B7FED8" authorityName="Aurivillius" authorityYear="1904" box="[852,984,313,334]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Erlandia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="372" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inopinata">
<emphasis id="8DCF7442FF8F8A15896CFEC591B7FED8" box="[852,984,313,334]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="372">E. inopinata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="78BBD3D3FF8F8A158E29FEC593EBFEFF" authorityName="Di Iorio" authorityYear="1998" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Erlandia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="372" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="megacephala">
<emphasis id="8DCF7442FF8F8A158E29FEC593EBFEFF" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="372">E. megacephala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in ‘‘El Chaco’’ (
<bibRefCitation id="DB2AD5A1FF8F8A158807FEA890B9FEFF" author="Di Iorio" box="[575,726,340,361]" pageId="4" pageNumber="372" pagination="1 - 4" refId="ref1928" refString="Di Iorio, O. R. 1998. The genus Erlandia Aurivillius, 1904 (Coleoptera: Cerambycidae) in Argentina, with the description of a new species. Insecta Mundi 12 (1 - 2): 1 - 4." type="journal article" year="1998">Di Iorio 1998</bibRefCitation>
) a phytogeographic region of north central 
<collectingCountry id="C7ACE8C0FF8F8A158B50FE9393BCFE12" box="[360,467,367,388]" name="Argentina" pageId="4" pageNumber="372">Argentina</collectingCountry>
, western 
<collectingCountry id="C7ACE8C0FF8F8A158805FE9390F1FE12" box="[573,670,367,388]" name="Paraguay" pageId="4" pageNumber="372">Paraguay</collectingCountry>
and the southeast of 
<collectingCountry id="C7ACE8C0FF8F8A1589B5FE9391B5FE12" box="[909,986,367,388]" name="Bolivia" pageId="4" pageNumber="372">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="DB2AD5A1FF8F8A1589D3FE939320FE09" author="Sarmiento" pageId="4" pageNumber="372" pagination="233 - 251" refId="ref2153" refString="Sarmiento, G. 1975. The dry plant formations of South America and their floristic connections. Journal of Biogeography 2: 233 - 251." type="journal article" year="1975">Sarmiento 1975</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="78BBD3D3FF8F8A158B5BFE76938AFE09" authorityName="Noguera &amp; Chemsak" authorityYear="2001" box="[355,485,394,415]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Erlandia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="372" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mexicana" status="new species">
<emphasis id="8DCF7442FF8F8A158B5BFE76938AFE09" box="[355,485,394,415]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="372">E. mexicana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="96FCC939FF8F8A158BD5FE769004FE09" box="[493,619,394,415]" pageId="4" pageNumber="372" rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
is found in the floristic province of the Valley of Tehuacán­Cuicatlán, which is situated in south central 
<collectingCountry id="C7ACE8C0FF8F8A1589B8FE5991BFFE2C" box="[896,976,421,442]" name="Mexico" pageId="4" pageNumber="372">México</collectingCountry>
between the states of 
<collectingRegion id="7D7F66B2FF8F8A158B40FE3C93D0FE43" box="[376,447,448,469]" country="Mexico" name="Puebla" pageId="4" pageNumber="372">Puebla</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion id="7D7F66B2FF8F8A158BCEFE3C902BFE43" box="[502,580,448,469]" country="Mexico" name="Oaxaca" pageId="4" pageNumber="372">Oaxaca</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation id="DB2AD5A1FF8F8A15886CFE3C912EFE43" author="Villasenor" box="[596,833,448,469]" pageId="4" pageNumber="372" pagination="293 - 301" refId="ref2180" refString="Villasenor, J. L., P. Davila, and F. Chiang. 1992. Fitogeografia del Valle de Tehuacan- Cuicatlan [Pp. 293 - 301]. In: Biogeography of Mesoamerica. Proceedings of a Symposium. (S. P. Darwin and A. L. Welden, editors). Tulane Studies in Zoology and Botany. Supplementary Publication No. 1. New Orleans. 342 pp." type="book chapter" year="1992">
Villasenor 
<emphasis id="8DCF7442FF8F8A1588F3FE3C916EFE43" box="[715,769,448,469]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="372">et al.</emphasis>
1992
</bibRefCitation>
). Hypotheses about distribution patterns of insects in 
<collectingCountry id="C7ACE8C0FF8F8A15886FFE2790C8FE66" box="[599,679,475,496]" name="Mexico" pageId="4" pageNumber="372">México</collectingCountry>
indicate that the endemic fauna of the Mexican Plateau have an ancient Neotropical origin (dispersion) (
<bibRefCitation id="DB2AD5A1FF8F8A158E30FE0A9321FDB0" author="Linsley" pageId="4" pageNumber="372" pagination="1 - 97" refId="ref2044" refString="Linsley, E. G. 1961. The Cerambycidae of North America. Part I. Introduction. University of California Publications, Entomology 18: 1 - 97." type="journal article" year="1961">Linsley 1961</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="DB2AD5A1FF8F8A158B64FDED939FFDB0" author="Halffter" box="[348,496,529,550]" pageId="4" pageNumber="372" pagination="1 - 64" refId="ref1972" refString="Halffter, G. 1976. Distribucion de los insectos en la zona de transicion mexicana. Relaciones con la entomofauna de Norteamerica. Folia Entomologica Mexicana 35: 1 - 64." type="journal article" year="1976">Halffter 1976</bibRefCitation>
; Kohlman and Halffter 1988) or is a remnent of tropical biotas existing in America before the separation of North and South America (vicariance) (Michener and Grimaldi 1988; 
<bibRefCitation id="DB2AD5A1FF8F8A1588DCFDBA9112FDCD" author="Noguera" box="[740,893,582,603]" pageId="4" pageNumber="372" pagination="9 - 60" refId="ref2122" refString="Noguera, F. A. 1993. Revision taxonomica del genero Oncideres Serville en Mexico (Coleoptera: Cerambycidae). Folia Entomologica Mexicana 88: 9 - 60." type="journal article" year="1993">Noguera 1993</bibRefCitation>
). Under this context, 
<bibRefCitation id="DB2AD5A1FF8F8A158B2FFD9D93BCFDE0" author="Sarmiento" box="[279,467,609,630]" pageId="4" pageNumber="372" pagination="233 - 251" refId="ref2153" refString="Sarmiento, G. 1975. The dry plant formations of South America and their floristic connections. Journal of Biogeography 2: 233 - 251." type="journal article" year="1975">Sarmiento (1975)</bibRefCitation>
has indicated that the dry tropical floras of southern South America (including ‘‘El Chaco’’) do not have a very close relationship with the flora of northern South America and that the later are more related, at least the 
<taxonomicName id="78BBD3D3FF8F8A158B78FD4E93C2FD51" box="[320,429,690,711]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="4" pageNumber="372" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Cactaceae</taxonomicName>
, with the dry formations of 
<collectingCountry id="C7ACE8C0FF8F8A1588E2FD4E9142FD51" box="[730,813,690,711]" name="Mexico" pageId="4" pageNumber="372">México</collectingCountry>
. This discontinuity supports the hypothesis of a very old divergence among these biota and that it is a result of an event of vicariance. However, stronger evidence is necessary for this to be more conclusive. A determination of the time of divergence among the species of 
<emphasis id="8DCF7442FF8F8A158B82FCE29071FCA5" box="[442,542,798,819]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="372">
<taxonomicName id="78BBD3D3FF8F8A158B82FCE29075FCA5" authorityName="Aurivillius from" authorityYear="1904" box="[442,538,798,819]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Erlandia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="372" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Erlandia</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
would help to support or reject either of these hypotheses or both.
</paragraph>
